summaries.title: Summary 285.1
summaries.summaryText: She recounted experiences where her technical contributions were overlooked and strategies she used to assert confidence. [Part 2/4]

summaries.title: Summary 285.2
summaries.summaryText: Ethan discussed observing classmates who struggled to access tutoring or networking opportunities. His reflection on his own privilege as a continuing-generation student led him to advocate for more peer tutoring support and accessible design lab hours. [Part 4/4]

summaries.title: Summary 285.3
summaries.summaryText: Luis found the shift from project-based high school learning to theory-heavy coursework challenging but rewarding. [Part 1/4]

summaries.title: Summary 285.4
summaries.summaryText: Luis found the shift from project-based high school learning to theory-heavy coursework challenging but rewarding. [Part 3/4]

timelinePoints.eventDescription: Co-founded a mentorship initiative within NSBE for first- and second-year engineering students. [Timeline 3]
Presented senior capstone project on sustainable urban drainage systems, earning department recognition. [Timeline 2]
Faced subtle exclusion in a group design project where her ideas were initially dismissed. [Timeline 3]
Co-founded a mentorship initiative within NSBE for first- and second-year engineering students. [Timeline 4]

themes.title: Emotional Labor and Advocacy Burden in Underrepresented Students
themes.description: Aaliyah’s experience illustrates how women of color in engineering often balance advocacy roles with academic demands, leading to invisible emotional labor that institutions rarely acknowledge. [Extended 4]

themes.title: Navigating Institutional Barriers as a First-Generation Student
themes.description: First-generation identity shapes how Maria interprets bureaucratic and academic systems, creating additional cognitive and emotional labor compared to continuing-generation peers. [Extended 4]

themes.title: Team Diversity as an Engineering Strength
themes.description: Ethan believes interdisciplinary and culturally diverse teams drive better innovation outcomes, reflecting the growing importance of social awareness in engineering practice. [Extended 2]

quotes.quoteText: My parents don’t really understand what I study, but they tell everyone I’m going to be an engineer — that means a lot, but it’s also scary. [Context 4]
I realized I had access to engineering summer camps that most of my friends never even heard of — that’s when privilege clicked for me. [Context 4]
When I walk into a classroom and see no one who looks like me, I remind myself that my presence opens the door for someone else. [Context 2]
Sometimes I look around my class and I’m the only Latina — it makes me question whether I belong here. [Context 4]
Seeing other Latina engineers at the SHPE conference made me feel like I’m not alone — like I really do belong in this field. [Context 3]
My parents always say 'you represent the family'—it motivates me but also adds pressure. [Context 2]
You can’t innovate if you’re burned out — STEM needs to start treating wellness as part of success. [Context 3]
I love leading projects, but it’s exhausting always being the one to explain why diversity matters in engineering teams. [Context 1]

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Peer Mentoring for First-Generation STEM Students
areasForImprovement.description: Formalize mentoring programs that pair upperclassmen with first-generation students early in their academic journey. These networks reduce imposter syndrome and improve retention rates. [Extended 4]

areasForImprovement.title: Broaden Access to Early Engineering Exposure Programs
areasForImprovement.description: Ethan’s reflection highlights unequal early access to STEM exposure. Partnering with local schools and community programs can help level the playing field for underrepresented groups. [Extended 2]
